Would you like me to now connect these dropdowns and radio buttons to the Spring Boot backend with YAML-driven values (the main.yml + multiple field YAMLs setup)?















You‚Äôre absolutely right ‚úÖ ‚Äî you don‚Äôt have an app.module.ts, because your app is standalone (Angular 10.9.2 standalone setup using AppComponent + ApplicationConfig).
Thanks for catching that ‚Äî we‚Äôll fix it without adding a module file.

Let‚Äôs fix all three errors properly inside your existing standalone setup:


---

‚ö†Ô∏è The Errors You Mentioned

1. ‚ÄúNeither ngFor directive nor CommonModule was imported‚Äù
‚Üí You need to import CommonModule in every standalone component that uses *ngFor or *ngIf.


2. ‚ÄúRouterOutlet is not a known element‚Äù
‚Üí Import RouterOutlet in your AppComponent (which you already do, but we‚Äôll double-check).


3. ‚ÄúCan‚Äôt bind to formGroup since it isn‚Äôt a known property of form‚Äù
‚Üí You must import ReactiveFormsModule in your standalone component where the form is defined.




---

‚úÖ Here‚Äôs how to fix everything

üü¢ app.ts

Make sure your root component imports RouterOutlet and CommonModule (you already had this mostly right).

import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { Router, RouterOutlet } from '@angular/router';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [RouterOutlet, CommonModule],
  templateUrl: './app.html',
  styleUrls: ['./app.css']
})
export class AppComponent {
  menuOpen = false;

  constructor(private router: Router) {}

  toggleMenu() {
    this.menuOpen = !this.menuOpen;
  }

  navigateTo(path: string) {
    this.menuOpen = false;
    this.router.navigate([path]);
  }
}


